{"questionId":"9067391","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">The equations show steps in the formation and decomposition of ozone in the stratosphere, some of which absorb ultraviolet light.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\"><br>Step 1&nbsp; &nbsp; O<sub>2</sub> → 2O•</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">Step 2&nbsp; &nbsp; O• + O<sub>2</sub> → O<sub>3</sub></span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">Step 3&nbsp; &nbsp; O<sub>3</sub> → O• + O<sub>2</sub></span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">Step 4&nbsp; &nbsp; O• + O<sub>3</sub> → 2O<sub>2</sub></span></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">Distinguish ultraviolet light from visible light in terms of wavelength and energy.</span></p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">«UV» shorter wavelength <em><strong>AND</strong> </em>higher energy «than visible» ✔</span></p>","meta":{"questionId":"9067391","referenceCode":"19N.2.sl.TZ0.1c","subjectId":"45-dp-chemistry-last-assessment-2024","title":"Distinguish ultraviolet light from visible light in terms of wavelength and energy.","paper":"2","level":"SL","questionNumber":"c","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Core","Core","Topic 2: Atomic structure","2.2 Electron configuration","Core","Topic 2: Atomic structure"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}